## 4. The "Hand Feel" Experience

- Impact Sensation
    - Hardness Words: Firm and solid, but not like a brick. Plays closer to a 49 or 50-degree hardness.
    - Feedback: Very direct and clear. You know exactly where on the racket you struck the ball.
    - Hold vs. Release: Excellent hold when hitting hard; quick, dead release on soft touches.
    - Dwell Time: Moderate-to-high, strictly dependent on your impact power.

- Sound/Click
Produces a sharp, solid "crack" rather than a metallic ESN "click" when engaged properly.

---

## 5. Compatibility & Setup Guide

- Best Blade Matches
    - Outer Carbon: Not recommended unless the blade has significant flex. If the blade is too stiff, the throw angle becomes unmanageably low.
    - Inner Carbon: The sweet spot. Blades like the W968 or Innerforce ALC provide the necessary flex to lift the ball.
    - All-Wood: Excellent match (e.g., Stiga Clipper). Helps raise the throw angle, provides a massive sweet spot, and maximizes touch.
    - Mismatch Cases: Extremely stiff and fast composite blades (e.g., Tamca 5000) will make it feel like it only has two speeds: a slow push and an uncontrollable missile.

- Forehand vs. Backhand Recommendation
    - Forehand: Highly recommended. Perfectly suits a power-oriented forehand wing.
    - Backhand: Only for advanced players with elite mechanics who prefer a punchy, low-throw backhand.

